// lang/english.tra

@1 = ~ZZ steam badge collection items "This is not cheating, your honor"~

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// ZZSTICK
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@1001 = ~The Bonker~

@1002 = ~A.k.a. The Murderstick, also filed as: Quarterstaff of Final Collection

The Bonker comes from the administrative layer beneath the planes: scripts, opcodes, saves, globals, death variables, dialogue states, and old warnings marked "do not touch".

It separates enemies with valid paperwork from enemies wasting animation time.

Not fair combat. Steam badge collection.

Operational Warning:
Let dialogue, transformations, surrender states, journal updates, phase changes, and death scripts finish before final collection.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
- Strikes as a +6 weapon
- MAX attacks per round
- Main attack: melee at 40ft range
- Alternate attack: ranged beholder-ray magic damage projectile
- On hit: removes dispellable protections without level comparison or credential review
- On hit: discourages troll-related clerical delays
- On hit when bonking: no-save slay target

Special abilities:
- I see you:
  Instant True Sight-style audit. Invisibility, illusions, and hostile concealment paperwork are revoked immediately.
- Papers, Please:
  Enemy-area dispel and summon cleanup. Effects without nondispellable authorization are authoritatively removed.
  "But I am an ancient lich" is not a document.
- The Harvest:
  Enemy-area final processing. Hostiles without proper immunity paperwork play their final animation. No save. No magic resistance.
  Use after quest paperwork is complete. Overharvesting may cause poor judgment.

THAC0: auto-hit or administratively equivalent
Damage ("melee"): BIG
Damage (ranged): small
Damage type: crushing
Speed Factor: irrelevant
Proficiency Type: Quarterstaff
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 someone tired enough to equip it

Weight: 4~


// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// ZZHEAD
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@1011 = ~Halo of Certainty~

@1012 = ~A.k.a. Headwear of Impossible Competence

The Halo of Certainty appeared where test items, prototypes, and "temporary" debugging tools become permanent.

It shines, hums, and can be seen from orbit.
This has no bearing on stealth checks.
Visibility is sensory. Stealth is a form field.

The halo corrects scheduling defects: locks, traps, spell limits, wild surges, fog of war, daily memorization, and similar frictions.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
- Improved Alacrity while worn
- Major spellcasting speed improvement
- Arcane and divine spell slots greatly expanded where applicable
- Wild surge bonus sufficient to encourage intended spell behavior
- Thieving skills improved enough that success should no longer be a planning variable
- Viewing distance at practical maximum
- Luck bonus
- Infravision
- Non-Detection

Special abilities:
- Logistic Correction:
  Once per rest, performs instant rest-grade correction. Spells, innate abilities, item charges, fatigue, and daily schedules are restored.
  The encounter requested mushrooms. The wearer had pineapples. Logistics corrected the discrepancy in the blink of an eye, because full-day preparation is for mere mortals.
- Cartographic Appreciation:
  Reveals the local map without outdoor objections, so the artistic department's work may finally be seen.
- Not on Today's Docket:
  Invisibility and administrative unavailability for hostile attention.
  This protects irrelevant enemies from unnecessary death, loot piles, pathing clutter, and being processed despite carrying no quest variables, unlocks, required items, or meaningful comedy.
  Survival should not be mistaken for relevance.
- Knock, Politely:
  Attempts to unlock what is unlockable. Intended for wearers without proper lockpicking buttons.
  The Knock fairy may accept the request, if the office provides proper paperwork.

Limitations:
Does not provide wisdom, restraint, or immunity to shiny buttons.

Requires:
 a head willing to become a filing cabinet

Weight: 1~

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// ZZBODY
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@1021 = ~Garment of Immunity~

@1022 = ~Also filed as: Wearable Refusal of Status Flags

The Garment of Immunity formed where planar law, engine habit, and player impatience agreed that some effects should stop being funny.

It does not grant courage. It grants refusal.
Ordinary magic is refused by magic resistance. Ordinary consequences are refused by saving throws. Ordinary violence gets lost among weapon immunity, resistance, and minimum-hit-point paperwork.
Explicit refusal is reserved for effects that remove agency, corrupt the character sheet, or turn solo badge collection into a reload prompt.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
- Defensive adjustment: administratively excessive
- Saving Throws: sufficiently reduced
- Magic Resistance: sufficient to keep refusing ordinary magic
- Physical, elemental, magic-damage and poison resistances: complete
- Minimum hit points: 1
- Minimum ability scores: 1
- Protection from Evil, mostly so gated visitors remember their place
- Explicit protection from known no-save/no-MR nonsense
- Explicit protection from selected agency-theft, forced-movement, character-sheet corruption and reload-prompt effects
- Immunity to critical hits
- Immunity to normal weapons
- Immunity to magical weapons
- Immunity to Time Stop

Special abilities:
- Ledger Correction:
  Removes dispellable effects from the wearer. Beneficial, hostile, accidental, theatrical, and embarrassing entries are not distinguished.
  Cures poison and disease. Removes curse. Restores levels and ability scores. Clears minor residue. Heals the wearer.
  If an effect wished to survive, it should have filed nondispellable authorization.
  The wearer is advised not to become attached to temporalities.

Limitations:
Does not protect against cutscenes, scripted placement, invalid use, broken scripts, curiosity, or processing a quest encounter before the quest form has closed.

Armor Class: sufficiently low
Requires:
 a character tired of reload prompts

Weight: 7~